   934                              <1> copyPathspec:
   935                              <1> ;1) Copies a path portion from the source buffer to the destination
   936                              <1> ;2) Advances rsi to the next null, \ or /
   937                              <1> ;3) Expands all * to ?'s
   938                              <1> ;4) Understands \. means "this directory" and can be ignored with rsi moving to
   939                              <1> ;    next path separator and rdi pointing to the previous pathsep
   940                              <1> ;5) Understands \.. means "parent directory" and rdi should be changed to rbx
   941                              <1> ;    with rsi moving to path separator
   942                              <1> ;6) Each name in destination is at most 12 chars long, to account for the dot
   943                              <1> ;
   944                              <1> ;INPUT:     rsi = First char of pathspec to qualify
   945                              <1> ;           rdi = Points to where to store it
   946                              <1> ;
   947                              <1> ;RETURN:    rsi = First char of next pathspec or past terminating null
   948                              <1> ;           rdi = First char of next space to store next pathspec
   949                              <1> ;           al = Last char stored (either \ or NULL)
   950                              <1> ;           CF=NC = OK path
   951                              <1> ;           CF=CY = PATH OR FILE NOT FOUND
   952                              <1> ;               IF A WILDCARD FOUND IN A SUBDIR NAME, RETURN PNF.
